data.name: Staff / Work Private Network
data.description: Staff may only authenticate and access any of these internal systems while connected to the work network. To work from home staff may use a VPN to connect to the system. This allows easy mitigation of Denial of Service Threats and generally hardens the system against malicious actors.

threats.title: Malicious actor gains access to account
threats.description: Hacker is able to obtain email and password and login as the applicant. Therefore gaining access to sensitive application and personal information
threats.mitigation: This could be mitigated by educating users about password security or with two-factor authentication.

threats.title: Malicious actor gains access to account
threats.description: A malicious actor could access to an owner's account by stealing their credentials in some way.
threats.mitigation: This could be mitigated by educating users about password security or with two-factor authentication.

data.name:
Authenticated
Staff Member
data.description: All actions from authenticated staff members first undergo token authentication to confirm the staff member is authenticated.

threats.title: Malicious Actor acquires staff credentials
threats.description: A malicious actor may be able to authenticate as a staff member. This may be achieved through any number of exploits, such as a re-used password or directly exploiting the auth database.
threats.mitigation: Effective logging of all authenticated staff member actions should be used. In the case that it becomes known that a staff member's account has been compromised, it will be possible to effectively trace the actions of a malicious actor.

threats.title: Leak of Applications and PII of Applicants
threats.description: Applications are confidential, particularly because they contain PII data relating to owners and applicants.
threats.mitigation:
Effective logging, and ensuring the public application system boundary is well hardened.
Only store the data that is needed.

threats.title: Effective Logging required to mitigate uncontrolled database access
threats.description: If a malicious actor is able to extract data either through a process or through direct access to the database, we want to know what data they have extracted.
threats.mitigation: Add sufficient logging and log retention to all database access to understand how the database may have been exploited.

threats.title: Leak of Application Documents and PII of Applicants
threats.description: Applications are confidential, particularly because they contain PII data relating to owners and applicants.
threats.mitigation:
Effective logging, and ensuring the public application system boundary is well hardened.
Only store the data that is needed.

threats.title: Malicious Actor updates tokens to gain access
threats.description: A malicious actor with access to this token database may effectively write any auth token to any staff member. This would allow the actor to authenticate as anyone they wish, allowing a repudiation attack.
threats.mitigation: Effective logging on all KV accesses. Harden this system and ensure it is difficult for a malicious actor to attack.

threats.title: DoS
threats.description: Because this process is not gated by any authentication, it would be easy for a malicious actor to attempt a denial of service attack.
threats.mitigation: Place the service behind a proxy that defends against DoS.

data.name: Communicate Staff Member's Login Details
data.reasonOutOfScope: Communicated out of band over some existing communication channel.

data.name: Token
data.description: Pre check to be conducted before all requests, ensuring staff members has a valid authentication token.

threats.title: Leak of Auth Token
threats.description: Leaking the auth token could result in malicious actors acting as authenticated staff members.
threats.mitigation: Only send auth tokens over TLS.

threats.title: Leak of Supporting Documents
threats.description: Supporting documents are considered confidential.
threats.mitigation: Supporting documents should only be communicated over TLS encrypted channels.

threats.title: Adversary in the document modifies supporting documents
threats.description: An adversary-in-the-middle modifies the supporting documents displayed to the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Adversary in the middle changes the status
threats.description: An adversary-in-the-middle intercepts the request to consult progress and modifies the status displayed to the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Supporting documents can be stolen
threats.description: An adversary in the middle can steal the supporting documents of the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Adversary in the middle changes supporting documents
threats.description: An adversary-in-the-middle intercepts the supporting document upload and supplies their own document with modified content.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Personal data can be stolen
threats.description: An adversary in the middle can steal the PII of the applicant.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Adversary in the middle changes applicant details
threats.description: An adversary-in-the-middle intercepts the application submission and modifies applicant details.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Supporting documents can be stolen
threats.description: An adversary in the middle can steal the supporting documents of the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Adversary in the middle modifies supporting documents
threats.description: An adversary in the middle modifies supporting documents that are displayed to the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Adversary in the middle changes application status
threats.description: An adversary-in-the-middle intercepts the request to consult progress and modifies the status displayed to the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Personal data can be stolen
threats.description: An adversary in the middle can steal the personal data of the user.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Adversary in the middle changes owner details
threats.description: An adversary-in-the-middle intercepts the application submission and modifies owner details.
threats.mitigation: Use Transport Layer Security (TLS) for the communication.

threats.title: Leak of Credentials
threats.description: Credentials may be leaked if communicated over an insecure channel. If staff credentials are leaked, significant customer data may be disclosed to malicious actors.
threats.mitigation: Only communicate secrets over TLS.

threats.title: Staff sign in DoS attack
threats.description: The sign in page could suffer a DoS attack.
threats.mitigation: Place the internal staff features of the application behind a firewall/on an intranet that is not accessible to the open web.

threats.title: Potential leak of username details
threats.description: If the login page provides a different error message when attempting to authenticate with a username that exists, compared to the error message for a username that does not exist, it is possible that usernames will get leaked. This is not a significant issue but is a concern.
threats.mitigation: Provide the same error message and response payload for usernames that do and do not exist.

data.name: Admin User
data.description:
Superuser setup at system start.
Capable of adding and removing Staff user accounts.

threats.title: Malicious Actor alters staff credentials
threats.description: A malicious actor with access to the database may change a staff's credentials, this could enable a repudiation attack in which the malicious actor successfully authenticates as any staff member.
threats.mitigation: Effective logging of all database accesses and frequent database backups.

data.name:
Unauthenticated
Staff Member
data.description: Unauthenticated staff members are able to authenticate and then become Authenticated Staff Member Actors.

threats.title: DoS Attack
threats.description: The Consult Progress service which is public facing could face a DoS attack.
threats.mitigation:
Place the service behind a proxy that defends against DoS attacks.
Log access IPs.
